text: I think this is in reality Chazelle's story, like Whiplash was, but on a bigger scale. A jazz enthusiast who never stopped trying to incorporate his favorite music into films for a broad audience, despite everyone rejecting his ideas and calling Jazz an extinct genre. Who knows what personal sacrifices he had to make to get his big break and now can do exactly what he wants with his own stories instead of cashing in. He had the script for this in 2010, but couldn't make it happen, since he didn't have a fan base and he would only make it with heavy alterations by the studios. It was shot and finished in 2015. Five years. That's how long it took for the couple to start out and become successful in their dreams. I hope he keeps it up, he's very young and can have many years of giving us great films like the ones he's already made.
author: Alexander Angelus

text: Today, movies lack magic. You always get your typical superhero films, mediocre Kevin Hart movies, crappy comedy B movies, and a ton of Oscar bait that generally takes itself too seriously. You rarely if ever get a film that has so much heart and soul that it can convince even the most shuttered and hollow skeptic of its magic. La La Land is the most magical film I've ever seen. It never took itself too seriously, it was funny when it needed to be, sad when it was appropriate, and endlessly entertaining. It never missed a beat. The planetarium scene in particular is one of the most breathtaking and awe-inspiring sequences I've ever seen in film. La La Land is the best film of 2016 and one of the best films of the decade so far.
